Combat Commander: Tournament Battle Pack &ndash; Leader of Men is the seventh themed collection of scenarios for use with the Combat Commander series of games. The growing and continued popularity of the Combat Commander Series has increasingly found its inclusion in game conventions around the globe.  In many instances these conventions pit the players in a tournament setting.  Invariably the question arises of how to implement and run such a tournament.  In an effort to formalize these endeavors the CC: Tournament Battle Pack was created to provide a core set of tested scenarios and rules for use in the running of a Combat Commander Tournament.

CC Tournament Battle Pack&ndash;Leader of Men features twelve scenarios (ten previously available online and two new) printed on cardstock, two new maps, four page tournament guidelines booklet, and tournament record card template printed on cardstock.

Each scenario is designed specifically for tournament play with situations and scenario special rules crafted to test a player&rsquo;s skill and Combat Commander knowledge.  The twelve scenarios cover actions from 1939 to 1944 with each of the combatants in the Combat Commander Series represented in at least one scenario.  The Tournament Guidelines Booklet contains the preferred rules the designer uses to implement and run tournaments at the World Boardgaming Championships and the PrezCon Game Convention.  These guidelines are an out of the box solution for any potential tournament host but are also easily adapted to suit any style of tournament play.

The scenarios included in CC Tournament Battle Pack&ndash;Leader of Men are:

&ldquo;Hill 133&rdquo;, German vs Russian, 1943, Map 24; 
&ldquo;Blitzkreig Unleashed&rdquo;, German vs Polish, September 1939, Map 12; 
&ldquo;A Midnight Clear&rdquo;, German vs US, December 1944, Map 3;
&ldquo;The Bridge Too Far&rdquo;, German vs British, September 1944, Map 17;
&ldquo;On the Road to Victory&rdquo;, British vs Italian, July 1943, Map 10;
&ldquo;One Steppe Beyond&rdquo;, German vs Russian, March 1943, Map 8; 
&ldquo;Signals in the Snow&rdquo;, Finnish vs Russian, November 1939, Map 20;
&ldquo;Codes in the Sunrise&rdquo;, German vs British, June 1940, Map 4;
&ldquo;Operation Mercury&rdquo;, German vs British, May 1941;
&ldquo;Barbarossa Unleashed&rdquo;, German vs Russian, June 1941;
&ldquo;Red Sector A&rdquo;, German vs US, 1944, New Map #73;
&ldquo;La Villa Strangiato&rdquo;, US vs Italian, 1944. New Map #72;


NOTE: CC Tournament Battle Pack&ndash;Leader of Men is not a complete game and requires ownership of Combat Commander: Europe and Combat Commander: Mediterranean to play.

Mr. Hop in Essen is a special promo card for Dice Brewing, which was available at Spiel '14, in Essen.

Mr. Hop in Essen is a recipe card which requires the following basic recipe: 

     1 hop die (green) with the minimum value of 2; 
     2 light malt dice (yellow), one with a minimum value of 3 and one with a minimum value of 5;
     1 dark malt dice (black) with the minimum value of 3;
     1 special hops token.


The player's reward is 5 master points and 6 gold coins. The card's enhancements are: 

     1 blue die for 2 mastery points;
     2 gold coins for an action token.


Mr. Hop can also be found in the rule book, as an employee from the Training Department who helps players navigate through the rule of the game.

SS Tiger Keil is a two-player war simulation game that recreates the extreme fighting opposing the German II SS-Panzer Corps and the Soviet 5th Guards Tank Army employing a modern and innovative twist in gameplay.

Prologue

&ldquo;&hellip;within the wide ranging continuous battle, a week after the Germans started Operation Zitadelle the Soviets finally launched powerful counterattacks against the Germans. One engagement stood out in the south at Prokhorovka, the 5th Guards Tank Army counterattacked the II SS-Panzer Corps, resulting in a large clash of armor just outside the settlement on 12 July 1943...&rdquo;

Estimates vary about the numbers involved but it generally thought that a combined total of over a thousand tanks clashed that day, which today proves to be incorrect.

Product

&bull; A &ldquo;classical&rdquo; revamped war board game portraying the 12th of July climatic battle at Prokhorovka;
&bull; Game concept complexity targeted at a specific audience such as: 
  &nbsp;&nbsp;o Memoir 44 players;
  &nbsp;&nbsp;o Axies & Allies players;
  &nbsp;&nbsp;o Although, very suitable to new or experienced wargamers;
&bull; Streamlined gameplay mechanics offer adequate pace of play;
&bull; Gameplay delivers operational and tactical feelings, depending on what the player is doing;

Quality Compliance

    Initial design captured 100% sourced realistic historical data (based on George Nipe Jr. study);
    Map and OOB reflects most updated information about the battle; 
    Game may reflect most updated and accepted outcome of the battle, but the game system guarantees that every game is totally different; 


Features

    Stacking: 1 combat unit per Hex;
    No CRT (no security echelons in combat);
    No Halving Calculations (only minor additions and subtractions);
    Armor range firing (up to 1.5 km for the Tiger I);
    LOS (1 rule);
    Maximization of Mechanics Streamlining (focused on learning pedagogics);


Scale

    A hex represents approximately 750 Meters of terrain from side to side;
    Each turn represents an average time span from 1 to 2 hours;
    Combat units are mostly infantry regiments, Mechanized, Tank Brigades and Panzer Kampfgruppe; 
    Some units add simple chrome to the game and gameplay;


Play Time

    Scenarios range from 1/2h to 4-5 Hours

